# Encapsulation: Deep Dive — Immutability, Defensive Copying, and the Builder Pattern

## Why Encapsulation Goes Beyond Getters and Setters
Beginner encapsulation means making fields `private` and adding getters/setters. Mature encapsulation means controlling all paths through which internal state can be read or modified, including through collections and mutable objects returned by getters.

```java
// Beginner — still broken encapsulation:
public class Order {
    private List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();
    public List<OrderItem> getItems() { return items; } // BROKEN: caller gets the internal list
}
// Caller: order.getItems().clear(); // destroys internal state from outside!

// Mature encapsulation:
public class Order {
    private final List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();
    public List<OrderItem> getItems() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(items); // read-only view
    }
    public void addItem(OrderItem item) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(item);
        items.add(item); // only way to add — goes through validation
    }
}
```

## Defensive Copying — Protecting Mutable Fields
When a constructor or setter accepts a mutable object (Date, array, List), store a copy, not the reference. When a getter returns a mutable object, return a copy or unmodifiable view.

```java
public class Promotion {
    private final LocalDate[] validDates; // mutable array!

    public Promotion(LocalDate[] dates) {
        this.validDates = Arrays.copyOf(dates, dates.length); // defensive copy on entry
    }

    public LocalDate[] getValidDates() {
        return Arrays.copyOf(validDates, validDates.length); // defensive copy on exit
    }
}
// Without defensive copying: caller holds the original array and can modify it;
// getter returns the internal array and caller can modify it.
```

## Immutable Classes — The Gold Standard
An immutable class has state that cannot change after construction. Thread-safe by design. No defensive copies needed for sharing.

Rules for immutability:
1. Declare class `final` (prevents mutable subclasses)
2. All fields `private final`
3. No setters
4. Defensive copy for mutable fields in constructor and getter
5. Return new object for all "modification" operations

```java
public final class Money {
    private final BigDecimal amount;  // BigDecimal is immutable — no copy needed
    private final String currency;

    public Money(BigDecimal amount, String currency) {
        this.amount = Objects.requireNonNull(amount);
        this.currency = Objects.requireNonNull(currency);
    }

    public Money add(Money other) {
        if (!currency.equals(other.currency)) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Currency mismatch");
        return new Money(amount.add(other.amount), currency); // returns NEW object
    }

    public BigDecimal getAmount() { return amount; } // safe — BigDecimal is immutable
    public String getCurrency() { return currency; }
}
```
`String`, `BigDecimal`, `LocalDate`, `LocalDateTime`, `Instant` — all immutable. This is why they're safe to share across threads.

## Builder Pattern — Encapsulation for Complex Object Creation
When a class has many optional fields, telescoping constructors become unwieldy:
```java
// Telescoping constructor nightmare:
new Order(id, customerId, items, deliveryDate, discountCode, priority, notes, warehouse, carrier, paymentMethod)
// Which param is the discount code and which is the priority?

// Builder solves this — fluent, self-documenting:
Order order = Order.builder()
    .id(UUID.randomUUID().toString())
    .customerId("C123")
    .items(List.of(item1, item2))
    .deliveryDate(LocalDate.now().plusDays(3))
    .discountCode("SAVE20")
    .priority(Priority.HIGH)
    .build(); // validation can happen in build()
```
Lombok's `@Builder` generates this automatically. Without Lombok:
```java
public static class Builder {
    private String id;
    private String customerId;
    // ... all fields ...

    public Builder id(String id) { this.id = id; return this; }
    public Builder customerId(String customerId) { this.customerId = customerId; return this; }

    public Order build() {
        Objects.requireNonNull(id, "id required");
        Objects.requireNonNull(customerId, "customerId required");
        return new Order(id, customerId, ...);
    }
}
```

## Encapsulation in Spring Boot
Spring Boot Data classes need encapsulation carefully balanced with framework requirements:
```java
@Entity
public class Order {
    @Id
    private String id;

    @OneToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
    private final List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();

    protected Order() {} // required by Hibernate — package/protected, not public

    public List<OrderItem> getItems() { return Collections.unmodifiableList(items); }
    public void addItem(OrderItem item) { items.add(item); }
    public void removeItem(String itemId) {
        items.removeIf(i -> i.getId().equals(itemId));
    }
}
```
`orphanRemoval = true` delegates item lifecycle management to the Order — a domain-driven encapsulation approach.

## Common Mistakes
1. **`public` JPA entities:** setters for all fields. Any code can corrupt the domain object's state.
2. **Returning `this.items` directly:** hands internal structure to the caller.
3. **Mutable Date in constructors without defensive copy:** `this.createdAt = createdAt` — caller modifies the date after construction.
4. **Builder without validation in `build()`:** invalid objects are created, failing later with cryptic errors.

